PSA_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The Psalter (150 poems spanning roughly David's reign to the post-exilic period) was the hymnbook of the Second Temple — used in liturgy from the restoration (Ezra-Nehemiah) through the NT period. The Dead Sea Scrolls (1QPs, 4QPsa-r, and 11QPsa) preserve the most psalms of any biblical book among the Qumran community, indicating the Psalter's centrality in Jewish worship. The Psalter is organized into five books (Ps 1-41, 42-72, 73-89, 90-106, 107-150) mirroring the five books of Moses, each ending with a doxology. The arrangement suggests a canonical editorial design: the Psalter tells the story of Israel's covenant relationship with YHWH from Torah-delight (Ps 1) to universal praise (Ps 150).</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 22 is the most cited OT Psalm in the NT Passion narratives. Its historical background (David's persecution?) is unknown — the Psalm presents an archetypal experience of abandonment and vindication. The pattern: intense lament (vv. 1-21) → sudden transition to praise (v. 22) → eschatological proclamation (vv. 27-31: 'all the families of the nations shall worship before you ... posterity shall serve him; it shall be told of the Lord to the coming generation'). The Psalm functions in NT usage not as a prediction of specific details but as the divinely-given interpretive framework for understanding the cross: suffering-unto-vindication, abandonment-unto-universal-proclamation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'O my God, I cry out by day, but you do not answer; by night I find no relief' — in the ancient world, divine silence was the gravest form of rejection. The day/night merism (continuous crying at both periods) indicates that the petitioner has exhausted every appropriate time of prayer without response. ANE petition texts regularly describe the persistent supplication of the worshiper and the expectation of divine reply; the failure to receive an answer implied either divine anger or divine absence. The Psalm names this experience honestly rather than theologizing it away.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'But you are holy, enthroned on the praises of Israel' — the theological pivot between vv. 1-2 (unanswered prayer) and vv. 4-5 (the ancestors' answered prayer). YHWH's holiness and transcendence do not negate the relationship but explain why his ways exceed understanding. 'Enthroned on the praises of Israel' (<em>yoshev tehillot yisrael</em>) — YHWH is not indifferent to worship; he dwells within it. The covenant history of Israel's praise is itself the throne from which YHWH exercises his faithfulness.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'In you our ancestors put their trust; they trusted, and you rescued them' — the appeal to covenant history as the warrant for present petition. The patriarchs, the Exodus generation, and the judges-era community all experienced divine rescue following trust. In Israelite prayer, historical precedent was legally relevant: YHWH's past faithfulness obligated future faithfulness under the same covenant terms. The ancestors' experience of deliverance is a data-point in the psalmist's case.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'They cried to you and were delivered; they trusted in you and were not put to shame' — the shame/honor dimension: in the ancient Near Eastern honor-shame culture, having one's trust vindicated was public honor; having it betrayed was public shame. The ancestors who trusted YHWH were not shamed — their trust was publicly rewarded. This is the precedent the psalmist invokes: YHWH has a documented record of not shaming those who trust him.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'But I am a worm and not a man, scorned by everyone and despised by the people' — extreme social dehumanization. In the honor-shame world, social contempt was a form of death: a person stripped of honor and reduced to the status of a contemptible creature (<em>tola'at</em>, a worm — among the lowliest of creatures) had no standing in the community. The contrast with vv. 4-5 is deliberate: the ancestors were honored by being rescued; this petitioner is being treated as sub-human. The reversal from vv. 9-10 (YHWH's favored one from birth) to v. 6 (socially abased) is the Psalm's central tension.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'All who see me mock me; they sneer and shake their heads' — the head-shaking gesture (<em>yani'u bero'sh</em>) was the conventional gesture of derision in ancient Israel and the ANE (cf. Lam 2:15: passersby 'clap their hands at you; they hiss and shake their heads at the daughter of Jerusalem'; Jer 18:16; Job 16:4). The mockery gesture was not merely emotional contempt but a social performance that communicated to all observers that the person was beneath consideration.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'He trusted in the LORD; let the LORD rescue him' — the logic of the mockers mirrors the exact reasoning of the passersby at the crucifixion (Matt 27:39-43: 'He trusts in God; let God rescue him now, if he wants him'). The taunt assumes that divine favor = divine rescue; the absence of rescue = absence of divine favor. This was the standard ANE interpretation of unremedied suffering: if the deity had not intervened, the petitioner had been abandoned. The taunt is theologically coherent within its framework and therefore devastating.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Yet you drew me out of the womb; you made me trust in you at my mother's breasts' — the birth-covenant: the psalmist's relationship with YHWH was not self-initiated but divinely given at the moment of birth. The language parallels the Servant of YHWH in Isaiah (Isa 49:1: 'The LORD called me before I was born; from my mother's womb he named my name'). Divine care from birth established a relationship that the present abandonment must be interpreted within, not against.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Upon you I was cast from birth; from my mother's womb you have been my God' — the casting (<em>hashlik</em>) onto YHWH at birth implies that the dependence on YHWH was not a later choice but the original condition of the psalmist's existence. In ancient Israel, the birth and naming of a child was a communally significant event; the child was placed in the care of YHWH from that moment. The psalmist presses this foundational covenant as the argument for divine response: you have been my God since birth — how can you be absent now?</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Do not be far from me, for trouble is near and there is no one to help' — the petition repeating the spatial contrast: YHWH is described as 'far' (vv. 1, 11, 19) while trouble is 'near.' In the patron-client system of ancient Israel, the patron's physical proximity was necessary for protection; a patron who was absent (whether geographically or relationally) could not defend the client. The declaration 'there is no one to help' is the client's formal statement that all human patrons have abandoned him, leaving YHWH as the only recourse.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Many bulls surround me; powerful bulls of Bashan encircle me' — Bashan was the fertile plateau east of the Jordan, famous for its rich pastureland (Deut 32:14; Amos 4:1; Ezek 39:18). The well-fed cattle of Bashan were among the largest and most formidable animals in the ancient Near East. 'Bulls of Bashan' as an image of powerful, well-fed enemies encircling the powerless psalmist contrasts the psalmist's wasted condition (vv. 14-15) with his opponents' abundance. The bull was also a royal and divine symbol in Canaanite religion (Baal as bull); the Psalm's enemies are as imposing as the symbols of opposing power.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'They open wide their jaws against me like a roaring, ravening lion' — the lion (<em>aryeh</em>) was the supreme predator in ancient Israel; its roar was both a literal sound and an image of irresistible power. The combination of bulls (powerful, encircling) and lion (rending, devouring) creates a compound image of the threat from all directions — surrounded and about to be consumed. Both animals were associated with royal power (Davidic lion imagery of 1 Kgs 10:19-20; the lion of Judah, Gen 49:9), here turned against the Davidic king.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'I am poured out like water, and all my bones are disjointed; my heart has turned to wax, melting within me' — extreme physical prostration. 'Poured out like water' = utter dissolution, inability to gather oneself. 'Bones disjointed' = the structural collapse of the body. 'Heart turned to wax' — the heart (<em>lev</em>) was understood as the seat of will and strength; its melting describes the complete collapse of courage and determination. These are physiological markers of extreme distress, possibly including shock or severe illness, described in the concrete bodily language of ancient medicine.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'My strength is dried up like a fragment of pottery; my tongue sticks to the roof of my mouth; you lay me in the dust of death' — extreme dehydration and proximity to death. A pottery shard without moisture is absolutely brittle; the tongue adhering to the palate is a classic symptom of severe dehydration in the ancient climate. 'The dust of death' (<em>aphar mavet</em>) is the grave: in the ancient cosmology, the dead returned to the dust from which they came (Gen 3:19). The psalmist is at the threshold of Sheol.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Dogs surround me; a mob of evildoers encircles me; they have pierced my hands and feet' — dogs in the ancient Near East were scavengers, not pets; they were associated with shame and uncleanness (1 Kgs 21:19: dogs licking Naboth's blood as divine retribution; Rev 22:15: dogs outside the holy city). A 'mob of dogs' surrounding the dying person is the image of the shameful, witnessed, public death. The 'piercing' of hands and feet: the Hebrew text is difficult (MT reads 'like a lion'); the LXX reads 'they have pierced' (<em>ōruxan</em>), which the NT Passion narratives presuppose.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'I can count all my bones; they stare and gloat over me' — visible emaciation as public shame. In the ancient world, physical deterioration was publicly visible (people lived in close proximity; the body was not hidden away). Counting visible bones = extreme wasting. The enemies 'stare and gloat' (<em>yab'itu yir'u-bi</em>) — witnessing the suffering as entertainment or as confirmation of deserved judgment. Public exposure of the suffering body was itself a component of punishment and shame in both Israelite and ANE legal practice.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'They divide my garments among themselves and cast lots for my clothing' — the dividing of a condemned person's clothing was the conqueror's right and the loser's ultimate dispossession. In Israelite law, the condemned man's property reverted to the community or the executor. The casting of lots for specific articles was a standard practice when multiple parties wanted the same object (cf. Num 26:55-56: lots for the division of the land; Neh 10:34: lots for wood-offering). John 19:23-24 applies this verse explicitly to the soldiers' division of Jesus's garments at the crucifixion.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'But you, LORD, do not stay far away! You are my strength; come quickly to help me!' — the petition following the extended lament. The 'but you' (<em>ve-attah</em>) is the pivot from description of suffering to direct address to YHWH. 'Far away' continues the spatial motif: YHWH who seemed distant is now directly addressed. The urgency ('come quickly') mirrors the urgency of the military situation described in vv. 12-18. The psalmist does not argue that YHWH should act because the suffering is unjust but because YHWH is 'my strength' — the covenant patron who has committed to support the client.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Rescue my life from the sword, my precious soul from the clutch of the dog!' — the sword (<em>cherev</em>) was the primary weapon of execution in ancient Israel; rescue from the sword = rescue from judicial or military death. 'The clutch of the dog' — returned to the dog image of v. 16: dogs as scavengers who consume the dead. 'My precious soul (<em>yechidati</em>)' — literally 'my only one,' the unique and irreplaceable self; the same word used for Isaac in Gen 22:2 ('your only son, the one you love'). The plea is for the preservation of the one irreplaceable life YHWH gave.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Rescue me from the lion's jaws! You have answered me from the horns of the wild oxen' — the 'wild ox' (<em>re'em</em>) was a fearsome beast of ancient Israel (mentioned in Num 23:22; Deut 33:17; Job 39:9-10). The horns of the wild ox were a standard image of irresistible power. 'You have answered me' — a sudden perfect tense breaks through the lament: the divine answer has already come. This pivot from petition to past-tense confidence in v. 21b is the hinge of the entire Psalm, after which the second half (praise and proclamation) flows.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'I will proclaim your name to my brothers; in the midst of the congregation I will praise you' — the transition from individual lament to communal proclamation. The 'brothers' (<em>achim</em>) are the covenant community gathered for worship. In Second Temple Judaism, public proclamation of YHWH's saving acts was performed in the assembly (<em>qahal</em>) as part of the thanksgiving sacrifice (<em>todah</em>) ceremony: the rescued person told the congregation of his deliverance. Hebrews 2:12 applies this verse directly to Christ proclaiming the Father's name to his brothers after resurrection.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'You who fear the LORD, praise him! All descendants of Jacob, honor him! Stand in awe of him, all descendants of Israel!' — the three-fold call to the covenant community to share in the rescued person's praise. The 'fear of the LORD,' honoring, and awe are three distinct postures of covenant worship ranging from reverent response to formal honor to solemn awe. The movement from 'those who fear the LORD' to 'descendants of Jacob' to 'descendants of Israel' is a widening circle: the devout, then the tribal community, then all of Israel — all summoned to corporate praise.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'For he has not despised or scorned the suffering of the afflicted one; he has not hidden his face from him but listened when he cried out to him' — the key theological affirmation: the appearance of divine abandonment (vv. 1-2, 11, 19) was exactly that — appearance, not reality. YHWH did not hide his face (the conventional metaphor for divine withdrawal of favor and presence). The 'face' (<em>panim</em>) of YHWH signifies covenant presence; its hiddenness means relational distance. That YHWH did not hide his face means the covenant was never broken even when it felt broken.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'My praise in the great congregation comes from you; I will fulfill my vows before those who fear him' — the <em>todah</em> (thanksgiving) vow ceremony: when in distress, the ancient Israelite would vow to offer a thanksgiving sacrifice and public proclamation if YHWH delivered him (cf. Ps 116:12-19). The fulfillment of the vow was performed publicly 'before those who fear him' — the assembled worshipers. The rescued person's testimony was part of the corporate liturgy of thanksgiving.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'The humble will eat and be satisfied; those who seek the LORD will praise him' — the communal dimension of the <em>todah</em> sacrifice: after offering the animal, the rescued person shared the meat with the poor (<em>anavim</em>, the humble). The feast following the thanksgiving sacrifice was a public redistribution of the gift of deliverance: the saved person feeding the hungry. The connection between individual rescue and communal generosity is built into the liturgical structure of thanksgiving worship.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'All the ends of the earth will remember and turn to the LORD, and all the families of the nations will bow down before him' — the remarkable eschatological expansion of the Psalm's scope: from one person's distress (v. 1) to the entire world's worship. The 'ends of the earth' (<em>afsei-arets</em>) encompassing all nations bowing before YHWH is the Abrahamic promise (Gen 12:3: 'all families of the earth shall be blessed through you') in Psalmic form. A personal lament becomes a universal promise — one of the widest trajectories in all of Scripture.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'For dominion belongs to the LORD, and he rules over the nations' — the theological ground of the universal worship envisioned in v. 27: YHWH's sovereignty is not limited to Israel or Zion but extends over all peoples. This is the same universalism as Ps 24:1 ('the earth belongs to the LORD and all its fullness'). The eschatological vision of all nations worshiping YHWH rests on the foundation of his actual cosmic sovereignty — it is not an aspiration but the expression of what already is cosmically true.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'All the prosperous of the earth will feast and worship; before him all who go down to the dust will bow — even those who cannot preserve their own life' — the comprehensive scope: both the prosperous (<em>deshnei eretz</em>) and the dying ('those who go down to the dust') worship. This is the full spectrum of humanity: the powerful and the utterly powerless both bow before YHWH. 'Those who cannot preserve their own life' may refer to the critically ill or the dying — even those unable to perform worship by conventional means are included in the eschatological assembly.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Descendants will serve him; the Lord will be declared to the coming generation' — the generational transmission of YHWH's saving acts was the core mechanism of covenant memory in ancient Israel: Deut 6:20-25 commands parents to tell their children the Exodus story when asked; Ps 78:2-4 describes the pattern of one generation teaching the next. The rescue narrated in Ps 22 is to be declared (<em>yesuppar</em>) to the next generation — becoming part of the ongoing covenant testimony.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'They will come and proclaim his saving acts to a people not yet born, declaring that he has done it' — the reach forward in time: the testimony of YHWH's saving act in this Psalm is projected to future generations not yet in existence. 'He has done it' (<em>ki asah</em>) is the conclusion of the proclamation — a completed-act declaration of divine faithfulness. This phrase has been identified as the functional equivalent of Jesus's 'It is finished' (<em>tetelestai</em>, John 19:30), which the early church saw as the declaration that the Ps 22 pattern was complete.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 23 is the most universally known of all the Psalms. The shepherd metaphor was a standard royal image across the ancient Near East: Hammurabi of Babylon called himself 'the shepherd of his people'; Egyptian pharaohs were depicted with the shepherd's crook and flail; Sumerian king Ur-Nammu was 'the faithful shepherd.' David was literally a shepherd before becoming king (1 Sam 16:11; 17:34-36), which gave the metaphor biographical as well as political depth. YHWH as Israel's shepherd appears in Ps 80:1 ('O Shepherd of Israel, hear us'), Ezek 34 (YHWH vs. the false shepherds), and Isa 40:11.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'He makes me lie down in green pastures; he leads me beside quiet waters' — pastoral geography of the Judean hill country. Green pastures (<em>niot deshe</em>) were seasonal in the dry climate; after the spring rains, the hillsides turned green briefly before summer drought. Still (<em>menukhot</em>, resting) waters rather than rushing streams: sheep will not drink from fast-moving water and can drown in flash floods in the Judean wadis. The shepherd's knowledge of terrain — where to find safe water and productive grazing — was specialized expertise that determined the flock's survival.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'He restores my inner life (<em>nephesh</em>); he guides me along right paths for the sake of his name' — the shepherd leads the sheep along known, safe paths (<em>magelei-tsedek</em>, tracks of righteousness) that reach productive grazing without danger. The metaphor carries moral weight: the 'right paths' are the covenant way. 'For the sake of his name' — YHWH's reputation as faithful shepherd-patron is at stake in whether he guides his people well. The shepherd's honor is bound to the flock's condition.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Even though I walk through the valley of deepest darkness (<em>ge tsalmavet</em>), I will fear no evil, for you are with me' — the shadowed ravines of the Judean hills where predators (lions, bears, wolves) lurked and where flash floods could trap flocks. Shepherds regularly led sheep through these valleys to reach highland pastures. 'Your rod and your staff, they comfort me' — the rod (<em>shevet</em>) was used to drive off predators (David describes using a staff against lion and bear in 1 Sam 17:35); the staff (<em>mishenet</em>) guided and recovered straying sheep from dangerous terrain. Both were tools of active protection, not passive presence.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'You set a table for me in full view of my enemies; you anoint my head with oil; my cup overflows' — the scene shifts from pastoral to royal banquet. The prepared table in the presence of enemies is the paradox of covenant abundance within threat. Shepherds literally anointed the heads of sheep with oil to repel insects in summer heat and to heal wounds from thorns; the practice was routine pastoral care. But the anointing here evokes royal anointing (1 Sam 10:1; 16:13) and priestly hospitality. The cup overflowing (<em>revayah</em>) is the abundance that exceeds what is needed.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Surely goodness and steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>) will pursue me all the days of my life, and I will live in the house of the LORD forever' — the reversal of the 'pursue' language that fills the lament psalms: enemies pursue the righteous (Ps 7:1; 109:16; 143:3); here it is YHWH's goodness and <em>hesed</em> that pursue. The committed covenant-loyalty of YHWH is not merely available but actively tracking the psalmist. 'The house of the LORD forever' — dwelling in YHWH's presence permanently; for the Psalm's original audience, the temple; in its fullest reach, eschatological presence.</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 24 is a liturgical psalm likely used in a processional for bringing the ark into Jerusalem (cf. 2 Sam 6) or in festival processions to the temple. 'The earth belongs to the LORD and all its fullness; the world and all who live in it' — the comprehensive sovereignty claim. In the ancient Near East, land was understood as divine possession apportioned to peoples and their patron deities (Deut 32:8-9: the Most High apportioned the nations to the sons of God). Ps 24:1 asserts YHWH's ownership of the entire earth, not just Israel's portion. Paul cites this verse in 1 Cor 10:26 to argue that idol-offered food remains under YHWH's ownership.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'For he founded it on the seas and established it above the rivers' — the ancient Israelite cosmology: the earth was conceived as established upon and surrounded by the cosmic waters (<em>tehom</em>, the deep of Gen 1:2; the waters beneath the earth of Exod 20:4). YHWH's act of founding the earth on the seas (<em>yamim</em>) and rivers (<em>neharot</em>) demonstrates his mastery over the primordial waters — the chaotic forces that pre-existed creation. This cosmological claim grounds the ownership claim of v. 1: the one who mastered chaos at creation owns what he created.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Who may ascend the mountain of the LORD? Who may stand in his holy dwelling?' — the entrance liturgy for temple worship. The 'mountain' (<em>har</em>) is Zion; the 'holy dwelling' (<em>qodesh</em>) is the temple. This entrance question (cf. Ps 15:1, which uses the same form) functioned as a formal challenge at the temple threshold: who has the moral-ritual standing to enter? The form was likely used in actual liturgical practice, with a priestly interrogation at the gates before admission to the sanctuary. Ps 15 and Ps 24 are the two primary entrance liturgy psalms.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'The one with clean hands and a pure heart, who does not set his mind on worthless things or make deceitful promises' — four criteria for temple access: (1) clean hands = ritual and moral purity (the hands were the instruments of action; clean hands = actions that are not morally compromised); (2) pure heart = inner moral integrity; (3) not setting the mind on worthless things = not pursuing idolatry or falsehood; (4) no deceitful oaths = covenant faithfulness in the realm of speech and legal witness. The criteria span from external ritual (hands) to internal orientation (heart) to speech (oaths) — the whole person examined.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'He will receive blessing from the LORD and vindication from the God who saves him' — the promise to those who meet the entrance requirements. 'Vindication' (<em>tsedakah</em>, righteousness/righteous standing) from the God who saves: covenant righteousness as the divine gift that grants the worshiper standing before YHWH. The temple entrance is not just permission to worship; it is the conferral of covenant status — the act by which YHWH declares the worshiper righteous before him.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Such is the generation of those who seek him, who seek the face of the God of Jacob' — the covenant community defined by its orientation: seeking (<em>dorshav</em>) YHWH and seeking his face (<em>panim</em>). 'Seeking the face' of a king was the formal act of approaching the sovereign in his court for judgment or favor (Esth 4:11; 2 Sam 14:24: Absalom could not 'see the king's face' = had no access to the royal presence). The temple worshiper 'seeks the face of the God of Jacob' — approaches the divine king in his heavenly court, the temple being the earthly access point.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Lift up your heads, you gates! Rise up, you ancient doors, so the King of glory may enter!' — the antiphonal processional liturgy, likely sung during an actual procession bringing the ark into Jerusalem (2 Sam 6) or in later festival processions to the temple. The gates and doors are personified and commanded to make way for the divine king. 'Ancient doors' (<em>pitche olam</em>, doors of eternity) — the gates of YHWH's royal city, permanent and majestic. The dramatic call-and-response structure (vv. 7-10) suggests actual performance with two groups: the procession and the gatekeepers (or two choirs).</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Who is this King of glory? The LORD, strong and mighty, the LORD, powerful in battle!' — the divine warrior identity. 'King of glory' (<em>melech hakavod</em>) — glory (<em>kavod</em>) as the radiant manifestation of divine power and majesty (Exod 16:10; 24:17; 40:34-35: the <em>kavod</em> filling the tabernacle at its dedication). The response names YHWH as the warrior-king: the ark that is being brought to Zion was the same ark that went before the armies of Israel in battle (Num 10:35-36; 1 Sam 4). Its entrance into Jerusalem is the triumphant procession of the victorious divine general to his throne.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Lift up your heads, you gates! Rise up, you ancient doors, that the King of glory may enter!' — the deliberate repetition of v. 7, intensifying the processional drama. In ANE processional texts and hymns (such as the Babylonian Akitu festival procession for Marduk), repetition with slight variation was a standard liturgical technique that built anticipation. The gates are addressed twice: once they hesitate or question (v. 8); the second call presses for compliance as the divine king's identity is now declared.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Who is this King of glory? The LORD of Armies (<em>Yhwh Tseva'ot</em>) — he is the King of glory!' — the climactic identification. <em>Yhwh Tseva'ot</em> (LORD of Armies/Hosts) is one of the most powerful divine titles in the OT: the commander of the armies of heaven (the divine council and angelic hosts) as well as Israel's armies on earth. The title appears frequently in the prophets (Isa 1:9; 6:3) and in the ark narrative (1 Sam 1:3: Eli's sons were at the tent of <em>Yhwh Tseva'ot</em>). The Psalm ends with this double identification: the procession's subject is the cosmic commander-king entering his royal residence.</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 25 is an acrostic: each verse (in Hebrew) begins with successive letters of the alphabet (aleph through tav), with some irregularities. The acrostic form was used in ANE literature (Babylonian acrostic wisdom texts date to the first millennium BCE) and throughout the OT (Ps 9-10, 34, 37, 111, 112, 119, 145; Lam 1-4). The artificial alphabetic constraint disciplines the poem while creating a sense of comprehensiveness — as if the petition covers the entire range of possibilities from aleph to tav. 'To you, LORD, I lift up my soul' — the gesture of raising the <em>nephesh</em> (soul/whole person) toward YHWH as complete offering and dependence.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'In you I trust; do not let me be put to shame; do not let my enemies triumph over me' — the primary social fear: public shame before enemies. In the honor-shame world of ancient Israel, to be 'put to shame' (<em>evoshshah</em>) was not merely embarrassment but the collapse of social standing and covenant relationship. Trust in YHWH was a public claim; if YHWH failed to vindicate the truster, the truster was publicly shamed. The petition is simultaneously personal (don't embarrass me) and theological (vindicate your faithfulness by vindicating me).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Indeed, no one who waits for you will be put to shame; those who betray without reason will be the ones shamed' — the covenant guarantee and the reversal principle. Those who wait (<em>qoveka</em>, your waiters) on YHWH are protected from shame. The traitors (<em>bogdim</em>) — those who break faith without cause — will receive the shame they sought to inflict on others. The principle of the boomerang: the shamer becomes the shamed; the honor-shame system's justice falls on those who exploit it.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Make your ways known to me, O LORD; teach me your paths' — the Torah-instruction petition. The 'ways' (<em>derachav</em>) and 'paths' (<em>orchotecha</em>) are the covenant wisdom that YHWH teaches; the request is for divine formation, not just divine action. Deut 4:5-8 presents YHWH's giving of the Torah as an act of wisdom-instruction — Israel's statutes and rules were wisdom visible to the surrounding nations. The psalmist asks to be a recipient of this same formation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Lead me in your faithfulness and teach me, for you are the God of my salvation' — '<em>emet</em>' (faithfulness, truth, reliability) as the quality of divine instruction: YHWH's teaching is not arbitrary command but reliable guidance aligned with how reality actually is. 'I wait for you all day long' — the extended, patient orientation toward YHWH that characterizes the 'waiting' person throughout the Psalter (cf. Ps 27:14; 37:7; 40:1; Isa 40:31: 'Those who wait for the LORD shall renew their strength').</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Remember your compassion (<em>rachamim</em>) and your steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>), for they have been from everlasting' — the two great covenant attributes of YHWH named in the Sinai self-revelation (Exod 34:6-7: 'The LORD, the LORD, a God merciful and gracious, slow to anger, abounding in steadfast love and faithfulness'). <em>Rachamim</em> (compassion) derives from <em>rechem</em> (womb) — the visceral maternal love of a mother for her child; <em>hesed</em> is the committed covenantal loyalty of a patron to a client. 'From everlasting' — these attributes are not reactive to Israel's goodness but characterize YHWH prior to and independently of Israel's conduct.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Do not hold against me the sins of my youth or my rebellions' — the explicit acknowledgment of a personal history of failures. 'Sins of youth' (<em>chato'ot ne'urim</em>) — the imprudent, headstrong errors of early life before wisdom matures. The petition is not that the sins be denied but that they not be 'remembered' against the psalmist — covenant forgetting as the divine act of removing guilt from the account (Jer 31:34: 'I will forgive their iniquity and remember their sin no more'). 'According to your steadfast love, remember me' — the positive request: let <em>hesed</em> be the framework for remembering, not the record of failures.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The LORD is good and upright; therefore he teaches sinners the right way' — the remarkable implication: YHWH's righteousness leads to his teaching of sinners rather than their immediate condemnation. The 'upright' (<em>yashar</em>) God's way of dealing with those who have gone astray is instruction (<em>yoreh</em>, Torah-teaching) rather than destruction. This is the grace embedded in the Law: the Torah is itself a form of divine mercy toward people who would otherwise not know the right path. The same logic underlies Ps 119's ecstatic love of the Torah as gift.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'He guides the humble (<em>anavim</em>) in justice and teaches the humble his way' — the <em>anavim</em> (humble, afflicted, poor in spirit) appear throughout the Psalter as those whom YHWH specially protects and instructs (Ps 22:26; 34:2; 37:11; 147:6; Isa 11:4; 61:1). In the social world of ancient Israel, the humble were often those without social power: the landless, the widow, the orphan, the foreigner. They were also those who, by their powerlessness, were forced to depend entirely on YHWH. Humility as receptivity to divine instruction is the social-spiritual disposition YHWH rewards with his teaching.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'All the LORD's paths are steadfast love and faithfulness for those who keep his covenant and his decrees' — the Deuteronomic covenantal framework: YHWH's ways are <em>hesed</em>-and-<em>emet</em> for those who maintain covenant loyalty. The formula '<em>hesed</em> and <em>emet</em>' (steadfast love and faithfulness) appears throughout the OT as the paired summary of covenant character (Exod 34:6; Gen 24:27; Josh 2:12-14). The condition 'for those who keep his covenant' is not merit-earning but covenant-claiming: the promise applies within the relationship, not outside it.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'For your name's sake, O LORD, forgive my guilt, for it is very great' — the appeal based on YHWH's name (reputation and character) rather than personal merit. The logic: because YHWH is the covenant-keeping God whose name encapsulates his faithfulness, forgiveness of a genuinely guilty person is an act that glorifies that name. The admission 'it is very great' abandons the strategy of minimizing guilt; the psalmist appeals to the magnitude of YHWH's mercy rather than the smallness of the offense.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Who is the one who fears the LORD? The LORD will instruct him in the way he should take' — the 'fear of the LORD' as the condition for divine instruction; the foundational principle of wisdom literature (Prov 1:7: 'the fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom'; 9:10; Ps 111:10; Job 28:28). The rhetorical question functions as a wisdom invitation: this is what it looks like to be the kind of person who receives divine teaching. The fear of the LORD is not terror but the reverent alignment with YHWH's authority that makes the person teachable.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'He will dwell in prosperity, and his children will inherit the land' — the covenant promise of material and generational blessing. 'Inherit the land' (<em>nochol arets</em>) echoes the central Deuteronomic promise: the land of Canaan as YHWH's gift to covenant-faithful Israel. The promise that the God-fearer's children inherit the land is the multigenerational dimension of covenant blessing (Deut 6:18: 'so that it may go well with you and that you may enter and possess the good land that the LORD your God swore to your ancestors'). Jesus's beatitude 'Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth' (Matt 5:5) directly alludes to this verse.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'The LORD confides (<em>sod</em>) in those who fear him, and makes his covenant known to them' — <em>sod</em> is the intimate council-chamber or inner circle of a king where classified information is shared (cf. Jer 23:22: the prophets who 'stood in the <em>sod</em> of the LORD' received authoritative revelation). To be in the <em>sod</em> of a great patron was a privilege of proximity available only to trusted intimates. Those who fear YHWH are brought into covenant intimacy — the inner circle of the divine king's counsel — and are given knowledge of the covenant that outsiders do not possess.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'My eyes are always toward the LORD, for he will free my feet from the trap' — the directional orientation of trust: eyes fixed on YHWH rather than on the threat. The 'trap' (<em>resheth</em>, net) is the image of enemies' hidden schemes — the social and legal traps set by adversaries that the psalmist cannot see or evade alone. Fixing the eyes on YHWH (who can see the whole terrain) rather than scrambling to avoid traps through human cleverness is the posture of covenant dependence.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Turn to me and be merciful to me, for I am alone and in distress' — 'alone' (<em>yachid</em>) in the honor-shame world meant catastrophically vulnerable: without family network, without patron, without advocates. Isolation was not merely emotional but social-structural; the solitary person had no recourse in the legal system (two or three witnesses were required; Deut 19:15), no one to pay debts, no one to avenge wrongs. The petition for divine mercy is the isolated person's only available appeal.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'The troubles of my heart have multiplied; bring me out of my anguish' — the compounding nature of affliction: troubles that multiply rather than resolve. The psalmist's anguish (<em>metsukotai</em>, straits/tight places) is the metaphor of geographical constriction — trapped in a narrow pass with no way out. The petition for rescue uses the same spatial metaphor: bring me out to the open where I can breathe and move.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Look at my affliction and my trouble, and forgive all my sins' — the direct linkage between affliction and sin: the request for forgiveness accompanies the request for practical rescue. In the ancient worldview, unresolved guilt was causally connected to ongoing affliction; removing the guilt (through divine forgiveness) removed the root cause of suffering. The petition does not argue that the affliction is unjust but appeals for mercy on the full complexity of the situation: trouble + guilt + need for both rescue and forgiveness.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Consider how many are my foes, and how violently they hate me' — the scale of opposition as an argument to YHWH. The enemies' hatred (<em>sinah chamah</em>, fierce hatred) is not ordinary social conflict but intense covenant-breaking hostility. In the ancient legal world, the number and intensity of opponents mattered: a lone accuser could be dismissed; many violent enemies constituted a social crisis requiring the superior authority of the divine court to adjudicate.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Guard my soul and rescue me! Do not let me be put to shame, for I take shelter in you' — the asylum language of covenant protection: taking shelter (<em>chasiti</em>) in YHWH as in the fortified city of refuge (Num 35:9-15 established cities of refuge for the accidentally guilty; YHWH as the ultimate sanctuary city). The shame-avoidance petition returns: the person sheltering in YHWH staked their honor on his faithfulness; to be put to shame would be to lose both the immediate crisis and the public declaration that trust in YHWH is reliable.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'May integrity (<em>tom</em>) and uprightness (<em>yosher</em>) protect me, as I wait for you' — the psalmist's own covenant character offered as protection, not as earning merit but as the covenant basis for claiming YHWH's faithfulness. 'Integrity' (wholeness, completeness of covenant loyalty) and 'uprightness' (straightness, alignment with the covenant path) are the psalmist's credentials — not a claim to sinlessness but to covenant orientation. The psalmist waits (<em>qiviti</em>) in the posture of expectant covenant trust.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Redeem Israel, O God, from all their troubles' — the acrostic Psalm, which began as individual lament and petition, closes with communal intercession. This movement from individual to communal is characteristic of the royal Psalms (the king's prayer extends to the people) and of the Psalter's editorial design (individual prayers within the covenant community's larger story). 'Redeem' (<em>pedeh</em>, ransom/buy back) is the Exodus vocabulary: YHWH who redeemed Israel from Egypt can redeem from present troubles. The individual experience becomes the template for national hope.</p>"
  },
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 26 is an oath of innocence, similar in form to Psalm 7. 'Vindicate me, O LORD, for I have walked in integrity and trusted in the LORD without faltering' — a legal appeal, not an assertion of moral perfection. The 'integrity' (<em>tumi</em>, wholeness/completeness) is covenant loyalty, not sinlessness. The psalmist immediately invites divine examination (v. 2) rather than asserting the verdict in advance — the confidence is in YHWH's ability to see clearly, not in the psalmist's reputation. The legal form recalls ANE oath-of-innocence procedures where the defendant submitted to divine scrutiny.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Test me, O LORD, and try me; examine my heart and my inmost self' — the invitation to divine omniscient scrutiny. 'Heart and inmost self (<em>kilyotai</em>, kidneys)' is the same pair as Ps 7:9: the complete interior life — the seat of thought/will (heart) and emotion/deep motivation (kidneys). Human courts could only evaluate external conduct and testimony; the divine court could examine the interior. By welcoming this examination, the psalmist claims confidence in the verdict: innocence that can withstand omniscient scrutiny.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Your steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>) is before my eyes, and I have conducted myself in your faithfulness' — <em>hesed</em> as the psalmist's motivating vision and governing principle. Having YHWH's <em>hesed</em> 'before the eyes' means seeing covenant loyalty as the operative reality within which all decisions are made. 'Conducted myself in your faithfulness' (<em>be-amitecha</em>, in your truth/faithfulness) — the claim is not that the psalmist was perfectly faithful but that YHWH's faithfulness was the framework within which the psalmist moved and decided. The basis is relational orientation, not performance record.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'I do not sit with deceitful men or associate with hypocrites' — the social dimension of covenant loyalty. In the ancient world, shared table and social association signified shared values and loyalties (cf. Ps 1:1's three stages of increasing involvement: walk/stand/sit with the wicked). Table-fellowship carried covenantal implications: eating with someone = alliance with them. The psalmist's refusal to sit with deceitful people (<em>anshei-shav</em>, men of vanity/emptiness) and hypocrites (<em>ne'alamim</em>, concealed ones, those who hide their true allegiance) is an act of covenant maintenance.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'I hate the company of evildoers and refuse to sit with the wicked' — the positive corollary of v. 4: active disassociation, not passive avoidance. The Hebrew 'hate' (<em>sane'ti</em>) here is not emotional hatred but the covenant's demand for clear separation (Deut 7:26: the Israelite who brings an abomination into their house shares in the curse; cf. Ps 97:10: 'You who love the LORD, hate evil'). The complete avoidance of the wicked's social environment is the standard set by Ps 1:1.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'I wash my hands in innocence and take my place at your altar, O LORD' — the hand-washing gesture (<em>erchatz beniqayon kapay</em>) was a legal declaration of innocence embedded in covenant law: Deut 21:6-7 prescribes the elders of a city washing their hands over a heifer when declaring their innocence of unresolved bloodguilt. Pilate's hand-washing in Matt 27:24 inverts this covenant gesture. The psalmist performs the declaration of innocence before approaching the altar — the right order of worship: legal self-examination before sacrificial offering.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Lifting my voice in thanksgiving and recounting all your wonderful works' — the proclamation of YHWH's saving acts as a component of temple worship. The <em>todah</em> (thanksgiving) ceremony involved verbal proclamation of YHWH's <em>niflaot</em> (wonderful works/miraculous acts) before the assembly. YHWH's 'wonderful works' in Exodus and wilderness wandering were the foundational acts proclaimed and re-proclaimed in worship (Ps 77:11-14; 78:4; 105:5; 106:2). Temple worship was partially structured around this ongoing proclamation of the covenant narrative.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'LORD, I love the dwelling place of your house and the place where your glory (<em>kavod</em>) lives' — temple devotion as the defining characteristic of the covenant person. The 'place where your glory lives' is the innermost sanctuary — the Holy of Holies where the <em>kavod</em> (radiant divine presence) manifested above the ark of the covenant (Exod 40:34-35: 'the glory of the LORD filled the tabernacle'; 1 Kgs 8:10-11: the <em>kavod</em> filling the temple at dedication). Attachment to the temple is attachment to the divine presence it houses.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Do not take away my life with sinners or with those who shed blood' — the petition not to be swept away with the wicked in divine judgment. In the ancient legal world, guilt by association was a recognized principle: those who allied with guilty parties could share their punishment (cf. Achan in Josh 7: his entire household executed with him; Korah's company in Num 16 swallowed with the rebels). The psalmist who has maintained distance from the wicked (vv. 4-5) now petitions for that distance to be recognized in the final judgment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'In whose hands are evil schemes and whose right hands are full of bribes' — the corruption of justice through bribery perverted the entire Israelite legal system. The 'right hand' was the instrument of oath-taking and covenant-making (Gen 14:22; Isa 62:8); a right hand 'full of bribes' is a hand desecrated — the oath-swearing instrument used for corrupt payment. Prov 17:23 states directly: 'A wicked person accepts a bribe in secret to pervert the ways of justice.' The psalmist's clean hands (v. 6) are contrasted with these bribe-filled hands.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'But as for me, I walk in my integrity; redeem me and show me your grace' — the final petition combines the covenant claim (integrity, v. 1) with the appeal for divine grace (<em>choneni</em>, be gracious to me). The psalmist does not presume on integrity as automatic entitlement but adds the request for grace: both the covenant standing and the divine favor are needed. The two are not in tension — the covenant standing is the basis for the claim; the grace is what YHWH adds beyond what the standing alone warrants.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'My foot stands on level ground; in the great congregation I will praise the LORD' — the concluding image of stable, vindicated standing. 'Level ground' (<em>mishaw</em>) is the stable, safe terrain of the vindicated person — contrasted with the 'slippery places' where the wicked stand (Ps 73:18). The 'great congregation' (<em>maqhel</em>) is the formal assembly of the covenant community in the temple: the psalmist's praise will be public, before the witnesses who matter, reversing the social shame that the petition sought to avoid. The Psalm that opened in legal crisis ends in anticipated public vindication.</p>"
  },
  "27": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 27 is read in Jewish liturgy during the Days of Awe — the period from Rosh Hashanah through Yom Kippur — reflecting its themes of divine protection, honest self-examination, and hope in the face of judgment. 'The LORD is my light and my salvation — whom shall I fear? The LORD is the fortress of my life — of whom shall I be afraid?' — the light metaphor for YHWH is relatively rare in the Psalter (cf. Isa 60:19-20; Mic 7:8). Light in the ANE was associated with divine presence, royal authority, and the dispelling of the darkness where enemies operated. Two protection metaphors: relational (savior/deliverer) and architectural (fortress/stronghold).</p>",
    "2": "<p>'When evildoers came against me to devour my flesh — my adversaries and foes — they stumbled and fell' — past enemies' military defeat as grounds for present confidence. 'Devour my flesh' is the language of total destruction; in ANE warfare, the defeated enemy's body being left for scavengers was the ultimate dishonor. The past tense ('they stumbled and fell') is the psalmist's testimony of prior divine protection, functioning as the empirical basis for the present confidence expressed in vv. 1, 3.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Even if an army surrounds me, my heart will not fear; even if war breaks out against me, I will still be confident' — the hyperbolic extreme: the worst-case military scenario (full army, open warfare) cannot shake the covenant confidence established by YHWH's proven protection. The confidence is not military self-assurance but trust in the divine patron whose track record (v. 2) justifies the claim. The language recalls covenant-warfare theology: 'What king, going out to encounter another king in war, will not sit down first and deliberate' (Luke 14:31) — but the psalmist's calculation rests on YHWH, not troop strength.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'One thing I have asked of the LORD, and that I will pursue: to dwell in the house of the LORD all the days of my life, to gaze on the beauty (<em>noam</em>) of the LORD and to seek him in his temple' — the concentration of desire on a single object. The 'one thing' petition was a known rhetorical form indicating absolute priority. 'Beauty' (<em>noam</em>) of the LORD — the divine 'pleasantness' or loveliness visible in the temple worship and the divine presence; the aesthetic dimension of holiness that attracts the worshiper. 'Seek him in his temple (<em>hekal</em>)' — the royal palace/temple as the court of the cosmic king; to seek the king in his palace is to pursue audience with the divine sovereign.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'In the day of trouble he will hide me in his dwelling; he will conceal me under the shelter of his tent; he will set me securely on a rock' — three protection images, each from a different register: (1) hidden in YHWH's house = the temple as asylum; (2) under the tent (<em>seter ohelo</em>) = the tabernacle tradition of divine covering (cf. the cloud covering the tabernacle, Exod 40:34-38); (3) on a high rock = the rock of the wilderness journey (YHWH as <em>tsuri</em>, my rock, throughout Psalms) and the elevated position inaccessible to enemies. All three converge on the temple as the ultimate place of covenant protection.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'And now my head will be raised above my enemies who surround me, and in his tent I will offer sacrifices with shouts of joy' — the honor-shame reversal: the bowed head raised high (cf. Ps 3:3: YHWH is 'the one who lifts my head'). The military surrounding becomes the occasion for the lifted head: the enemies who encircled the psalmist find themselves below his risen head. The 'sacrifices with shouts of joy' (<em>zivchei teruah</em>) are the <em>todah</em> (thanksgiving) sacrifices accompanied by the teruah — the joyful acclamation cry used in battle and in worship (Num 10:9; Ps 33:3; 47:1).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Hear, O LORD, when I cry aloud; be merciful to me and answer me' — the transition from the hymn of confidence (vv. 1-6) to direct petition (vv. 7-12) is characteristic of the 'psalms of trust': the psalmist both affirms confidence and acknowledges the ongoing need for divine response. The petition uses three verbs: 'hear' (<em>shema</em>), 'be merciful' (<em>choneni</em>), 'answer' (<em>aneni</em>) — the standard triad of the lament petition. The confidence of vv. 1-6 does not make petition unnecessary; it grounds the petition in the knowledge that YHWH can and does answer.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Seek my face — so you have spoken. My heart answers you: Your face, LORD, I am seeking' — the most intimate verse: YHWH's command to seek becomes the psalmist's responsive orientation. 'Your face' (<em>panim</em>) is the divine personal presence — the face-to-face encounter of covenant intimacy (Exod 33:11: YHWH spoke to Moses 'face to face'; Num 6:25-26: the Aaronic blessing invokes the shining face). To seek the face is to seek not merely divine help but divine presence itself. The psalmist's 'my heart says' shows that the response to YHWH's invitation is from the deepest interior — not performed seeking but genuine orientation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Do not hide your face from me; do not turn your servant away in anger. You have been my help; do not abandon or forsake me, O God of my salvation' — the inverse petition: having sought the face (v. 8), the psalmist now petitions against its hiddenness. Divine face-hiding is the classic metaphor for covenantal withdrawal of favor (Deut 31:17-18: YHWH hiding his face as covenant judgment; Ps 13:1; 44:24; 88:14). 'You have been my help' — past faithfulness invoked as the ground for continued faithfulness. 'Do not abandon or forsake me' (<em>al-ta'azveni ve'al-titsheni</em>) — the verb pair used of YHWH's permanent covenant commitment: Deut 31:6 assures Israel that YHWH 'will not leave you or forsake you.'</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Even if my father and mother abandon me, the LORD will receive me' — the extreme case invoked rhetorically: the most fundamental human bonds (parental) failing, yet the divine bond transcending them. The rhetorical form is a fortiori: if even parents (the most reliable human attachors) fail, YHWH's faithfulness remains. In ancient Israel, parental abandonment would mean social death: no inheritance, no advocacy, no support network. The promise that YHWH will 'receive' (<em>ya'asfeni</em>, gather in, adopt) the abandoned one is the claim that the divine patron's adoption supersedes the failure of the biological family.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Teach me your way, O LORD, and lead me on a straight path because of my enemies' — the Torah-guidance petition echoes Ps 25:4-5, 8-9: divine instruction as the path through the dangers posed by enemies. The 'straight path' (<em>orach mishor</em>, level/even road) keeps the psalmist from the traps and pitfalls set by adversaries. Enemies who use the legal system against the psalmist (v. 12: false witnesses) are countered by divine guidance that keeps the psalmist's conduct unimpeachable.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Do not hand me over to the will of my adversaries, for false witnesses have arisen against me and breathe out cruelty' — false witnesses (<em>edei-shaqer</em>) were among the most feared social threats in ancient Israel. Deut 19:16-21 legislated specifically against false witnesses: a false witness received the penalty they had intended for the accused. But before the verdict, the accused faced destruction: a conspiracy of false witnesses could overwhelm any defense. 'Breathe out cruelty' (<em>yafi'ach chamas</em>) — the violent speech of the witness as active force; false testimony as an act of violence against the innocent.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'I am certain I will see the goodness of the LORD in the land of the living' — the confident affirmation. The 'land of the living' (<em>eretz hayyim</em>) is this present life — the psalmist affirms hope for vindication in the current existence, not only eschatological resolution (contrast with Job who anticipates seeing YHWH 'after my skin has been destroyed', Job 19:26). The claim is present and temporal: I will see YHWH's goodness before I die, in this world, in this life. The Psalm's confidence grounds itself in the expectation of this-worldly vindication.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Wait for the LORD! Be strong, and let your heart be courageous; wait for the LORD!' — the doubled exhortation, perhaps addressed to the congregation rather than continuing personal prayer. The 'waiting' (<em>qaveh</em>) for YHWH is the characteristic posture of covenant faith throughout the Psalter and the prophets (Isa 40:31; Ps 25:3, 5; 37:7, 9; 62:1). Waiting is not passive resignation but active expectation — the stance of the sentinel who knows the sunrise is coming and watches for it. The bracketing of 'be strong and courageous' (<em>chazaq ve'amets libecha</em>) — used of Joshua entering the land (Josh 1:6) and of David before dying (1 Chr 22:13) — places this covenant confidence in the tradition of those who acted on YHWH's promise despite delay.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 110 is the most frequently quoted OT text in the NT. Jesus cites it in the Synoptics (Matt 22:41-46 and parallels) as a riddle about the Messiah's nature. Peter cites it at Pentecost (Acts 2:34-35). Paul cites it (1 Cor 15:25; Eph 1:20; Col 3:1). Hebrews cites or alludes to it eight times (1:3, 13; 5:6, 10; 6:20; 7:17, 21; 8:1; 10:12-13). Its dominance in NT Christology is due to its dual claim: (1) divine enthronement at God's right hand; (2) eternal Melchizedekian priesthood. These two — divine lordship and perfect priesthood — are the two Christological pillars the NT builds on from this one Psalm.</p>"
  }
}

PSA_CHRIST = {
  "2": {
    "7": "<p>A direct revelation: 'You are my Son; today I have begotten you.' The royal Psalm 2 reaches its Christological fullness in the resurrection. Paul at Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:33): God raised Jesus, 'as it is written in the second Psalm, You are my Son, today I have begotten you.' The 'today' of divine fatherhood is not the eternal generation alone but the specific day of the resurrection-enthronement, when the Son's identity is publicly declared. Every application of Ps 2:7 in the NT (baptism, transfiguration, resurrection) marks a moment when the Father publicly declares the Son's identity for the community to hear.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>A fulfillment: 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?' The Passion Psalm that Jesus cited from the cross is both a historical lament (David in extremity) and a Christological prophecy (the Son's abandonment in the atonement). The cry 'why have you forsaken me' is not a failure of faith but a genuine experience of divine absence — the moment when Christ bore the full weight of human sin-under-judgment. The Psalm's movement (dereliction → trust → vindication → universal proclamation) is the death-and-resurrection narrative in miniature. Jesus did not die in despair; the Psalm he cited ends in the world's worship of YHWH through the one who suffered.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The LORD says to my Lord: Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies your footstool.' The most foundational Christological oracle in the OT: the risen and ascended Christ is enthroned at the Father's right hand (the supreme position of divine authority) awaiting the final subjection of all enemies, including death (1 Cor 15:25-26). The present era is the era of Christ's enthronement: he reigns now, his enemies are being progressively placed under his feet, and the ultimate subjection is certain. Ps 110:1 frames the entire NT's understanding of the ascension and the present Christological situation of the cosmos.</p>",

    "4": "<p>A fulfillment: 'You are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek.' The divine oath of the eternal priesthood is fulfilled in Christ's resurrection, which established him as the priest who never dies. Unlike the Levitical priests who needed to offer sacrifice repeatedly and who were replaced by death, Christ offered himself once and lives forever in the power of an indestructible life (Heb 7:16, 24-25). The Melchizedekian priesthood — prior to Aaron, not from the tribe of Levi, without recorded end — is the OT's own signal that the Levitical system was provisional. Christ's eternal intercession ('he always lives to make intercession for them', Heb 7:25) is the fulfillment of Ps 110:4's oath.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_echo('psalms')
    merge_echo(e, PSA_ECHO)
    save_echo('psalms', e)
    print(f'Psalms echo: {len(e)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in e.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(c, PSA_ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'psalms', c)
    print(f'Psalms original: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(c, PSA_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms', c)
    print(f'Psalms context: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(c, PSA_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'psalms', c)
    print(f'Psalms christ: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
